, Somerset, England":"Brislington, Somerset, England","Wraxall, Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","Beaudesert, Warwickshire, England":"Beaudesert, Warwickshire, England","Saltford, Bath, Somerset, England":"Saltford, Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wickwar, Gloucestershire, England":"Wickwar, Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1165–1213":"about 1165–1213","1165–1213":"1165–1213","1155–1195":"1155–1195","1176–1231":"1176–1231","1125–1185":"1125–1185","1134–Female":"1134–Deceased","about 1181":"about 1181","1176":"1176","1231":"1231","1165":"1165","1185":"1185","1195":"1195","5 September 1195":"5 September 1195","1205":"1205","1213":"1213","1125":"1125","1134":"1134","Abt 1165":"about 1165","1155":"1155","about 1155":"about 1155","Brislington, Somerset, England":"Brislington, Somerset, England","Wraxall, Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","Beaudesert, Warwickshire, England":"Beaudesert, Warwickshire, England","Saltford, Bath, Somerset, England":"Saltford, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Wickwar, Gloucestershire, England":"Wickwar, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"la","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Hung, Cuong, Anh, Thanh, Ha, Hoang, Tuan, Chau, Hao, Hien, Hoa, Hue, Nam, Phong, Sinh, Tuong, Min, Tam, Tanh, Thai, Tham, Tinh, Yeong.  Chinese Hong, Hang, Sang, Tong, Chan, Chi, Hwa Ja, Hyung, Kam, Ki Bong, Kin, Man.","Vietnamese: from the Chinese surname 羅, see   Luo   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Lã</b>): from the Chinese surname 呂, see   Lu   6 and 3 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Luo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Jian, Yi, Ping, Yong, Zhen, Feng, Hong, Ming, Jin, Bin, Chen, Hai, Lan, Min, Huan, Hung, Shen, Tian.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 羅, meaning ‘net for catching birds’ or ‘to collect’ in Chinese: (i) from Luo (羅), the name of an ancient state (located in present-day Hubei province). After it was annexed by the state of Chu during the early Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ), people from the state migrated southwards and adopted Luo (羅) as their surname. (ii) from the Po Duo Luo (破多羅) and Chi Luo (叱羅) families from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China, who changed their original surnames to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) from the personal name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅), leader of an ancient Turkic tribe who are believed to have migrated to China during the Tang dynasty (618–907  AD ). His descendants inherited his name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅) as their surname and shortened it to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iv) from the name of one of the seven families from the Bandun Man, an ethnic group residing in ancient southwestern China (located mainly in present-day Sichuan province)."]}]},{"name":"Warre","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English:  see  Warr  .","2  English:  see  Ware  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Warr","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): nickname for a warrior, usually from Norman French <i>were</i>, <i>werre</i>, <i>waire</i>, <i>warre</i> (central French <i>guerre</i>) ‘war, battle’, and short for <i>de la werre</i> (<i>de la guerre</i>, see   Delaware  ), literally ‘(man) of the war’, a construction paralleled in <i>de la Bataille</i> (see   Battle  ). Occasionally it is a shortened form of Old French <i>werreur</i> ‘warrior’.","English: variant of   Ware  ."]},{"name":"Ware","meanings":["English:","topographic name for someone who lived by or looked after a dam or weir on a river (from Old English <i>wær</i>, <i>wer</i>, Middle English <i>war(e)</i>, <i>warre</i>, <i>wer(e)</i>, <i>werre</i> ‘weir’), or a habitational name from a place called with this word, such as Weare (Somerset), Weare Giffard (Devon), or Ware (Hertfordshire).","topographic name for someone who lived by a horse pond or fish pond, from Anglo-Norman French, Middle English <i>wayour</i>, which became early modern English <i>ware</i>, <i>wear</i>."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John de la Warre was born about 1165, in Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Jordan de la Warre, was 41 and his mother, Emma Bristolton, was 33. He married Joan de Gresley about 1181, in Brislington, Somerset, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1213, in Wickwar, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 49, and was buried in Saltford, Somerset, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1165–1213":"umbes 1165–1213","1165–1213":"1165–1213","1155–1195":"1155–1195","1176–1231":"1176–1231","1125–1185":"1125–1185","1134–Female":"1134–Surnud","about 1181":"umbes 1181","1176":"1176","1231":"1231","1165":"1165","1185":"1185","1195":"1195","5 September 1195":"5. september 1195","1205":"1205",